== DRAFTING NOTES (NON-BINDING) ==

Assumptions made during drafting:
- Change Date was set to four years from rough first-publication estimate
  (2030-06-16) as requested.
- License is based on Business Source License 1.1 (BSL 1.1) structure and
  operative terms. The standard BSL attribution regarding the MariaDB
  trademark is included.
- Governing law is set to South Africa for contractual predictability, with
  extensive carve-outs to preserve mandatory rights under Italian, Argentine,
  and EU law.
- English is the controlling language; translations are noted where
  enforcement practice may require them.

Points for a qualified attorney in each jurisdiction to review before
reliance:

SOUTH AFRICA:
- Review against the Consumer Protection Act 68 of 2008: confirm the warranty
  disclaimer and limitation of liability do not attempt to exclude liability
  that the CPA renders non-excludable (e.g., gross negligence, death, or
  personal injury). The current disclaimer reads down exclusions where
  mandatory law applies, but a specific analysis of classification (consumer
  vs. business) may be needed.
- Review against the Electronic Communications and Transactions Act 25 of 2002
  (ECTA): confirm electronic record, signature, and notice requirements are
  satisfied.
- Verify that the severability clause achieves the "read down, not voided
  wholesale" intent under South African contract law and that the High Court
  venue clause is enforceable.

ITALY / EU:
- Review the moral-rights clause under Italian Civil Code (Arts. 2575 et seq.)
  and EU law: confirm it appropriately preserves diritti morali and does not
  constitute an impermissible waiver.
- Identify which clauses may be "vexatious" (clausole vessatorie) under Arts.
  1341-1342 of the Italian Civil Code or counterpart EU consumer-protection
  directives. Determine whether specific written approval (approvazione
  specifica) from consumers is required for enforceability.
- Confirm that the liability carve-out for dolo and colpa grave satisfies
  Italian mandatory rules and that the governing-law clause does not defeat
  imperative consumer or author-protection norms.

ARGENTINA:
- Review under the Código Civil y Comercial de la Nación and Ley 11.723:
  confirm that inalienable moral rights are preserved and that the license
  does not purport to waive them.
- Verify that the limitation-of-liability clause complies with the
  prohibition on waiving liability for dolo and with any local consumer-
  protection or unfair-contract rules.
- Confirm that the South-African governing-law clause does not extinguish
  Argentine mandatory protections for local users.

GENERAL / COMMON LAW:
- Evaluate whether the competition restriction (offering the Licensed Work or
  a derivative as a competing UI engine / UI-as-a-service) is sufficiently
  certain to be enforceable and whether it raises antitrust or competition
  concerns in any relevant market.
- Verify that the automatic change-of-license mechanic (conversion to
  Apache-2.0 on the Change Date) is an enforceable obligation and does not
  constitute an illusory grant.
- Confirm the trademark clause adequately protects the marks "DarkBlaze",
  "Uni-UI", and "Sanity License" in key commercial markets and does not
  overreach vis-a-vis third-party marks.
- Determine whether a certified Italian or Spanish translation is required
  for enforceability in specific jurisdictions and, if so, the precise
  language the English text must be reconciled against.
